","1213":"1213","Abt 1200":"about 1200","1201":"1201","1200":"1200","1287":"1287","England":"England, United Kingdom","Addlington, Northampton, England":"Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom","Goxhill, Lincolnshire, England":"Goxhill, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","Scotton, Yorkshire, England":"Scotton, Yorkshire, England","Goxhill, Glanford Bridge, Lincolnshire, England":"Glanford Bridge, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Vere","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): habitational name, mostly from Vair in Ancenis, named with Gaulish <i>ver(n)-</i> ‘alder’. This was the probable home in the 11th century of the Breton lord Aubrey (Albericus) de Ver, who followed William the Conqueror to England and founded an influential family who held the earldom of Oxford until 1703. In a few cases the surname could be from other places in France, such as Ver in Manche and Calvados, which have the same etymology as Vair.","French (mainy Vendée; <b>Veré</b>): variant of <b>Vairé</b>, from Old French <i>vairie</i> ‘variegated, spotted’, applied as a nickname for someone who has freckles."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Walter","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, superseding the native Old English form, <i>Wealdhere</i>. It was a very popular name in medieval England, normally pronounced ‘Water’."],"variants":[{"name":"Walther","meanings":["from <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i> ‘army’; name of the famous medieval minnesinger  Walther von der Vogelweide  (  <i>c.</i>1170– <i>c.</i>1230 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Walter de Vere was born about 1184, in Scotton, Yorkshire, England, his father, Adam Goushill, was 32 and his mother, Gundreda Veer, was 32. He married Sibel de Kyme in 1202, in England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 3 sons. He died before 1213, in Glanford Bridge, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"Abt 1184–Bef 1213":"umbes 1184–enne 1213","1184–1213":"1184–1213","1185–1231":"1185–1231","1200–1270":"1200–1270","1200–1287":"1200–1287","–1270":"–1270","1154–1201":"1154–1201","1154–Female":"1154–Surnud","1154":"1154","1231":"1231","1185":"1185","Bef 1213":"enne 1213","1184":"1184","1270":"1270","Abt 1184":"umbes 1184","1202":"1202","1213":"1213","Abt 1200":"umbes 1200","1201":"1201","1200":"1200","1287":"1287","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Addlington, Northampton, England":"Northamptonshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Goxhill, Lincolnshire, England":"Goxhill, Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Scotton, Yorkshire, England":"Scotton, Yorkshire, England","Goxhill, Glanford Bridge, Lincolnshire, England":"Glanford Bridge, Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1184–Bef 1213":"noin 1184–ennen vuotta 1213","1184–1213":"1184–1213","1185–1231":"1185–1231","1200–1270"